&gt;  There is this large degree of worry about how various idiots
&gt;  will configure searching multiple default domains, usually
&gt;  expecting said idiots to use up valuable bandwidth or CPU time.
&gt;
&gt;  There is this large degree of worry about needing to search
&gt;  multiple default domains because various groups get to 
&gt;  administer their own space, because of : (choose n)

I still don't see what's wrong with just setting up a nickname
domain; i.e. a special domain that is everyone (everyone "around
here", that is) uses as their ONLY default domain and that just
contains CNAMEs that point off to the official stuff.

(1)  It gives me something I can control fairly easily and it gives
me a file that I can tell folks to search through so that they can
find out which nicknames are legal and which ones aren't and which
one are really close to what they were guessing.

(2)  It avoids the "get wrong answer a few times before getting the
right answer" phenomenon.

(3)  It works with old resolvers that can't do fancy domain searching
and obviates the need to recompile everything and retrain folks.

(4)  It gives me a method whereby I can avoid the problem of having
a situation that worked last week but doesn't work today.

Eric Norman &lt;ejnorman@unix2.macc.wisc.edu&gt;

